# This file records source mathematics that is not yet implemented in the
# executable Litex chapters. It is intentionally comment-only and is not
# exported by litex.config.

# Chapter 1 — Introduction; source labels FermatLastTheorem and hard.
# Missing mathematics: prove Fermat's Last Theorem for nonzero natural x, y,
# z and every exponent n greater than two. The upstream item is admitted with
# sorry, so this corpus does not present it as a checked Litex fact.

# Chapter 4 — Sets and Functions; source definition inverse and theorem
# inverse_spec.
# Missing mathematics: construct the source's total choice-with-default inverse
# on arbitrary carriers and prove its positive-preimage specification. This is
# genuine arbitrary choice, not the unique inverse available for an injective
# function.

# Chapter 4 — Sets and Functions; source section Schroeder-Bernstein.
# Missing mathematics: construct sbAux by recursive restricted images, define
# sbSet and the piecewise sbFun using the inverse branch, prove the right-
# inverse lemma and the injective and surjective branches, and assemble the
# resulting bijection. A future implementation must preserve these callable
# constructions rather than replacing them by proposition wrappers.

# Chapter 5 — Elementary Number Theory; source section Irrational Roots.
# Missing mathematics: prove the arbitrary-prime coprime-square obstruction;
# construct the callable prime_factor_exponent; prove factorization_mul,
# factorization_pow, prime_factorization_self, the parity obstruction, and
# power_equation_exponent_divisible. The implementation must first supply a
# checked decreasing-division definition and its multiplicity laws; the
# already checked p=2 parity proof is not a substitute for this interface.

# Chapter 5 — Elementary Number Theory; source construction MyNat and the
# theorems zero_add, succ_add, add_comm, add_assoc, mul_add, zero_mul,
# succ_mul, and mul_comm.
# Missing mathematics: construct the source's genuinely separate Peano carrier,
# its zero and successor constructors, its induction principle, and recursive
# addition and multiplication. Identifying MyNat with builtin N would erase
# the mathematical construction and is therefore not an implementation.

# Chapter 5 — Elementary Number Theory; source theorems
# exists_prime_factor_mod_4_eq_3 and primes_mod_4_eq_3_infinite.
# Missing mathematics: carry out the strong-induction factorization preserving
# residue 3 modulo 4, then use the source's Euclid-style number to prove these
# primes are unbounded. The elementary product-residue lemma itself is checked.

# Chapter 6 — Discrete Mathematics; source theorem finite_product_ne_zero.
# Missing mathematics: prove by finite-set induction that a product of natural
# numbers is nonzero when every factor is nonzero. The chapter currently has
# the finite-product object but no checked induction proof for this result.

# Chapter 6 — Discrete Mathematics; source theorems triangle_card and
# double_counting.
# Missing mathematics: count the ordered pairs 0 <= i < j <= n to obtain
# n * (n + 1) / 2, and prove the double-counting inequality by summing the row
# and column fiber cardinalities of a finite relation. The callable triangle
# set and its finiteness proof remain implemented in the chapter.

# Chapter 6 — Discrete Mathematics; source list definitions append and map,
# and theorems append_nil and map_map.
# Missing mathematics: construct the recursive append and map functions from a
# ListCore induction interface, prove their defining equations, and then prove
# the two structural-induction theorems. The checked ListCore, is_list_append,
# and is_list_map interfaces remain in source order.

# Chapter 6 — Discrete Mathematics; source construction BinTree, recursive
# functions size and depth, and theorem BinTree.size_le.
# Missing mathematics: construct the inductive binary-tree carrier and its
# recursion principle, define size and depth, and prove size <= 2^depth - 1 by
# structural induction. The independently useful nat_max function is checked.

# Chapter 6 — Discrete Mathematics; source construction PropForm, recursive
# functions eval, vars, and subst, valuation update, and theorems eval_eq_eval,
# subst_eq_of_not_mem_vars, and subst_eval_eq.
# Missing mathematics: construct propositional formulas with their induction
# and recursion principles, define these three recursive functions, and prove
# the agreement and substitution theorems. The finite Boolean carrier and its
# truth-table operations are implemented and checked in the chapter.

# Chapter 7 — Structures; source definition permGroup.
# Missing mathematics: prove associativity, identity, and inverse laws for
# reversed composition of self-equivalences, and assemble these operations into
# the permutation-group object. The equivalence operations themselves are
# implemented and checked.

# Chapter 7 — Structures; source Gaussian-integer commutative-ring instance.
# Missing mathematics: prove the additive and multiplicative ring laws for the
# coordinatewise Gaussian operations and assemble the commutative-ring object.
# The carrier, operations, coordinate equations, and norm laws are checked.

# Chapter 7 — Structures; source centered integer remainder and Gaussian
# Euclidean-domain construction.
# Missing mathematics: prove the centered quotient-remainder identity and the
# half-divisor bound, use those bounds to show that a nonzero Gaussian divisor
# gives a strictly smaller remainder norm, and assemble the resulting quotient,
# remainder, and rank into the Gaussian Euclidean-domain object.

# Chapter 8 — Hierarchies; source Ring3 additive-commutativity theorem and
# integer Ring3 instance.
# Missing mathematics: derive commutativity of addition from the source's ring
# axioms, verify those axioms for the ordinary integer operations, and assemble
# the corresponding integer ring object.

# Chapter 8 — Hierarchies; source selfModule, nsmul1, zsmul1, and abGrpModule.
# Missing mathematics: construct generic natural and integer scalar
# multiplication by recursion on the scalar, prove their defining and module
# laws, and assemble the self-module and canonical integer-module objects.

# Chapter 8 — Hierarchies; source product and integer AddMonoid4 instances.
# Missing mathematics: construct the componentwise natural-scalar action on a
# product and the ordinary natural-scalar action on the integers, then verify
# the AdditiveMonoidWithNSmul laws for both objects.

# Chapter 8 — Hierarchies; source SubMonoid1Monoid.
# Missing mathematics: restrict the ambient multiplication and identity to a
# submonoid carrier and prove that the restricted operations form a monoid.
# Intersection closure of submonoids is already checked.

# Chapter 8 — Hierarchies; source quotient projection, quotient multiplication,
# and quotient monoid.
# Missing mathematics: prove that the class projection lands in the quotient,
# that multiplication of representatives is independent of representatives,
# and that the induced operation and identity form a monoid. The equivalence
# relation and its reflexive, symmetric, and transitive laws are checked.

# Chapter 9 — Groups and Rings; source group normalization, homomorphism,
# subgroup, finite-group, and conjugation results.
# Missing mathematics: derive inverse uniqueness and the standard group
# normalization laws; prove group homomorphisms preserve identity and inverse;
# prove closure and membership results for subgroup map, comap, kernel, range,
# closure, and join; and carry out the source Lagrange, Sylow, subgroup-
# cardinality, coprime-intersection, and conjugation arguments. The carrier-
# first group, homomorphism, subgroup, and conjugate-set interfaces remain
# implemented, and subgroup intersection closure is checked.

# Chapter 9 — Groups and Rings; source permutation group, free group, and
# presented-group constructions.
# Missing mathematics: construct inverse permutations and prove the permutation
# group laws; construct reduced words and the free-group universal lift; and
# construct the quotient by relations used for the presented-group example.
# Direct permutation composition and identity remain implemented, but they are
# not presented as a completed group construction.

# Chapter 9 — Groups and Rings; source actions, orbit-stabilizer, cosets, and
# quotient-group theorems.
# Missing mathematics: prove Cayley's map injective, the orbit-stabilizer and
# quotient-times-subgroup equivalences, representative independence of quotient
# multiplication and inverse, the quotient group laws and lift, and the group
# first-isomorphism theorem. Actions, orbits, stabilizers, coset carriers,
# normal-subgroup data, and the quotient carrier remain implemented.

# Chapter 9 — Groups and Rings; source generic ring identities, units, quotient
# rings, ideal products, first isomorphism, and Chinese remainder theory.
# Missing mathematics: prove the generic square expansion, the forward integer-
# unit classification, unit inverse/group/map constructions, quotient-ring
# operation and lift well-definedness, ideal-product containments, quotient-
# kernel equivalences, and the finite Chinese remainder induction and
# isomorphism. The ring, unit, ideal, ideal-map, kernel, range, and quotient
# carriers remain implemented; the reverse integer-unit direction is checked.

# Chapter 9 — Groups and Rings; source polynomial construction and results.
# Missing mathematics: implement X, constants, polynomial addition and
# multiplication by finite coefficient sums, composition, evaluation, natural
# degree, roots, degree laws, and the bivariate circle example. The finite-
# support polynomial carrier and coefficient evaluator remain implemented.

# Chapter 10 — Linear Algebra; source dependent products and direct sums.
# Missing mathematics: construct the dependent product and finite-support
# direct-sum carriers, inclusions and projections, their universal maps, and the
# finite-index equivalence. The checked binary product and coproduct interfaces
# are not used as a substitute for these dependent constructions.

# Chapter 10 — Linear Algebra; source kernel, range, quotient-space, and first-
# isomorphism results.
# Missing mathematics: prove the injective-kernel and surjective-range
# equivalences; prove quotient projection typing and representative-independent
# addition and scalar multiplication; construct compatible lifts; and prove the
# quotient-by-kernel equivalence with the range. The kernel, range, quotient
# carrier, and lift-compatibility relationship remain implemented.

# Chapter 10 — Linear Algebra; source polynomial endomorphism theory.
# Missing mathematics: implement finite polynomial evaluation on endomorphisms,
# construct and characterize minimal and characteristic polynomials, connect
# roots with eigenvalues, and prove Cayley-Hamilton. Eigenvalue and eigenspace
# witness conversions themselves are checked.

# Chapter 10 — Linear Algebra; source matrix inverse and basis-coordinate
# constructions.
# Missing mathematics: select a two-sided matrix inverse from invertibility;
# construct basis evaluation and coordinate representation, finite linear
# combinations, Basis.mk and basis-constr, canonical function bases, toMatrix,
# finite indexed matrix multiplication, and the change-of-basis formula. The
# relational matrix-inverse and basis interfaces remain implemented.

# Chapter 10 — Linear Algebra; source dimension results.
# Missing mathematics: select ambient and subspace dimensions from finite
# bases, prove positivity and finite-index equivalences, the sum/intersection
# dimension formula and subspace bound, and equinumerosity of arbitrary basis
# index sets. Finite dimensionality and subspace-dimension existence remain
# honest relationships rather than selected numeric objects.

# Chapter 11 — Topology; source filter laws and real-filter limits.
# Missing mathematics: prove the principal/map/comap equivalences and
# composition laws, combine eventual facts, identify the real at-point filter,
# and prove the retained limit-algebra theorems. The filter families, map,
# comap, tendsto, and eventuality relationships remain implemented.

# Chapter 11 — Topology; source metric-space analysis.
# Missing mathematics: prove continuity of distance and quadratic examples,
# closed-set and closure characterizations, the neighborhood-basis theorems,
# compact-interval and extreme-value results, compact sets closed,
# Heine-Cantor, the Cauchy characterizations, completeness consequences, the
# geometric-step criterion, and the Baire theorem. Metric laws, balls,
# convergence, compactness, Cauchy, completeness, and density interfaces remain
# implemented; the real-distance and ball-center facts are checked.

# Chapter 11 — Topology; source induced/coinduced, separation, extension, and
# sequential compactness results.
# Missing mathematics: prove the induced/coinduced comparison, continuous-map
# composition, Hausdorff uniqueness, regular refinements, dense-set extension,
# first-countable closure/sequence equivalence, convergent-subsequence result,
# and finite-open-subcover theorem. The topology, open/closed, neighborhood,
# separation, density, first-countability, and compactness relationships remain
# implemented; the open-preimage continuity equivalence is checked.

# Chapter 12 — Differential Calculus; source selected derivative and elementary
# derivative theorems.
# Missing mathematics: prove uniqueness of an epsilon-defined derivative,
# construct the total derivative with its differentiable and nondifferentiable
# laws, supply real sine and pi from a real-analysis library, and prove the sine,
# sum, fifth-power, and sine-at-pi derivative examples.

# Chapter 12 — Differential Calculus; source extrema, Rolle, and mean value
# theorems.
# Missing mathematics: derive zero derivative at a local minimum, then follow
# the source auxiliary-function arguments for Rolle's theorem and the mean
# value theorem. The local-minimum, interval, continuity, and differentiability
# relationships remain implemented.

# Chapter 12 — Differential Calculus; source norm continuity, finite-
# dimensional completeness, and operator norm.
# Missing mathematics: prove the reverse-triangle one-Lipschitz inequality,
# transfer Cauchy convergence through a finite basis, and construct the operator
# norm as a supremum with its two characteristic inequalities. Normed-space,
# completeness, continuous-linear-map, and operator-bound relationships remain
# implemented; the identity map has a checked bound-one proof.

# Chapter 12 — Differential Calculus; source selected Frechet derivatives,
# higher derivatives, and inverse function theorem.
# Missing mathematics: prove derivative uniqueness before selecting fderiv,
# construct multilinear iterated derivatives and finite-order smoothness, and
# carry out the quantitative local-inverse construction with its two inverse
# laws and inverse derivative. Candidate Frechet and strict Frechet derivative
# relationships and continuous linear equivalences remain implemented.

# Chapter 13 — Integration and Measure Theory; source elementary integration.
# Missing mathematics: construct oriented interval integrals, uniform Riemann
# sums or an equivalent integrability foundation, logarithm and reciprocal
# behavior, total real derivatives, and whole-line integrals; then prove the
# identity and reciprocal formulas, both fundamental theorems of calculus, and
# the real convolution formula.

# Chapter 13 — Integration and Measure Theory; source extended nonnegative
# reals and ENNReal-valued measure results.
# Missing mathematics: construct ENNReal with zero, infinity, order, infinite
# sums, infima, and conversion to real; specialize the checked generic
# countably-additive measure interface; and prove measurable-superset infimum
# and countable-subadditivity results. Sigma-algebra closure, including the
# countable-intersection proof, and the generic disjoint-union measure law are
# checked.

# Chapter 13 — Integration and Measure Theory; source Bochner integration and
# major integration theorems.
# Missing mathematics: construct strongly measurable and integrable function
# carriers, Bochner and set integrals and their basic laws, product measures and
# product integrals; prove dominated convergence and Fubini; and develop the
# Jacobian, convolution, and change-of-variables results. Almost-everywhere
# truth remains implemented through a measurable zero-valued exceptional set.
